{
  "texts": [
    "cDPO Under a noisy preference dataset where the labels have been flipped with some small probability ϵ ∈ (0, 0.5), Mitchell (2023) propose to apply conservative DPO (cDPO) loss L cDPO.",
    "Let the loss in Eq. 2 be denoted as L DPO (y c, y r; θ).",
    "Then L cDPO is defined as a weighted mixture of L DPO:",
    "where ỹ denotes a sample from the potentially noisy dataset and the input prompt x is omitted for the simplicity of exposition.",
    "Note that the preference is flipped in the second term, which resembles label smoothing approach (Szegedy et al., 2016)."
  ]
}